did.head: Papers Summary
did.unittitle: John N. Rowe III papers
did.abstract: The John N. Rowe III papers consist of original manuscripts, legal documents, financial bonds, currency, and printed items relating to the early history of Texas and Mexico, as well as some early United States documents. Included are rare autographs of Stephen F. Austin, Sam Houston, and James W. Fannin.
did.langmaterial: English, Spanish, German, French, and Latin

bioghist.head: Biography/Profile
bioghist.p: John N. Rowe III was born to John Nelson and Margaret Elizabeth Rowe around 1937 in Dallas, Texas. From a young age, he began collecting bank notes, and this hobby soon turned into a passion. He began donating his collection of papers to The Texas Collection in 1985, with the last donation in 1991.
Today, Rowe is one of the foremost numismatic dealers in the United States, earning the Lifetime Achievement Award from the Professional Numismatic Guild in 2009.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: The John N. Rowe III papers span from 1510 to 1989, with the bulk of the material covering 1830-1880. The papers predominately deal with Galveston county, though Nacogdoches, Texas and New Orleans, Louisiana are also featured prominently. The majority of the papers were originally identified individually and that detail of processing is maintained throughout. The materials are now divided into three series: I. Spanish Documents, II. Early Texas Documents, and III. Early United States Documents.

The first series, Spanish Documents, contains Spanish language materials from Spain and Mexico. There are religious proclamations, political declarations, general correspondence, and financial records in this series. It also contains a concentration of documents about Puerto Rico and a group of around 150 documents to and from a Señor Antonio de Perez Galvez.

The Early Texas Documents series contains materials that are pre-Republic of Texas up to the early 20th Century. You can find many of Austin's Old 300 in this section of the papers. It is further divided into four subseries: correspondence, legal, financial, and other. The correspondence subseries consists of general correspondence of different individuals, among them Sam Houston, Stephen F. Austin and Moses Austin. The largest section, legal, consists of materials covering land grants, land titles, wills, marriages, court documents, and documents pertaining to legal representation. Notably in this subseries are two muster rolls from the Army of The Republic of Texas in 1840. The muster rolls are of Company E, 1st Texas Infantry Regiment, under Colonel Edward Burleson. The third subseries, financial, is made up of financial documents in the form of treasury warrants, inventories, receipts, bonds, Republic of Texas and Civil War currency, and checks. Other, the fourth subseries, contains materials in other languages than English and Spanish, early flyers, sheet music, invitations, tickets, circulars, publications, a section of letters and documents from the Stiles family, and a James W. Fannin letter from Cuba in 1832.
The third series, Early United States Documents, contains early materials from states other than Texas, correspondence, publications, treaties, Civil War currency, and United States currency.

The strength of the papers lies in the collective vision and nature of the documents themselves, first as historic pieces and then as a whole, and what they say about early Texas and Mexico. Each item is unique and valuable but, taken together, gives a broad glimpse into the legal, political and financial matters that helped to shape the state of Texas.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Prior to current processing, the John N. Rowe III papers were somewhat organized by number and name, and foldered down to the item level. After discussion, it was decided to go ahead and process the papers down to the item level. Along with processing at the item level, folders would be named according to names of individuals mentioned on documents within the folder when possible. A native Spanish speaker helped identify the names in the Spanish language documents, along with a Spanish professor who also served as a consultant.

Partial inventory lists were available for reference prior to this finding aid. Currently, the collection is organized in three series: I. Spanish Documents, II. Early Texas Documents, and III. Early United States Documents.

The Spanish documents contain a section of letters to and from a Señor Conde Perez Galvez and were numbered 1-151, and a section of letters dealing with Puerto Rico were numbered 152-237. That numbering system has been maintained physically, but the folders have been identified with names for ease of identification. Following the Puerto Rican section is a section that contains proclamations, decrees, municipal and state documents. The remainder of the Spanish series contains general correspondence that is arranged in alphabetical order.
The English Documents series is arranged alphabetically by last name within the different subseries, as is the United States Documents series.

Because these papers were collected individually for the most part, there is general inconsistency in the use of the word "and" as well as the ampersand (&) within the documents. This fact is reflected in the folder titles and headings, and these inconsistencies were kept in processing. Likewise, unusual or irregular spellings were also kept.

The condition of the documents range from extremely fragile to good. Most documents are sleeved and cannot be removed from their enclosures. Please use caution when handling these documents, especially any that are found unenclosed.

accessrestrict.p: All requests for copying of materials must be submitted to The Texas Collection in writing. Please use the Request Form for Copying Materials sheet. Unpublished materials authored or otherwise produced by the creator (s) of this collection are in the public domain. There are no restrictions on use. Archivist''s Notes: The John N. Rowe III papers were originally arranged using more than one system. 300+ folders were identified by the numeral one, two, three, and continuing from there. Another large group were arranged alphabetically, but not necessarily by the most famous or significant person named in the document. Some were not identified at all. Three-fourths of the collection was identified to the item level. Taking all this into consideration, it was decided to go ahead and process the whole collection to the item level rather than changed it. Where more than one name was evident within a document, as many names as could be identified were used on the folder titles.

did.unittitle: Spanish Documents

bioghist.head: Biography/Profile
bioghist.p: The Spanish Documents series contains correspondence, official municipal documents, preprinted government documents, incomplete documents, a ledger, receipts and a typewritten transcript. Notable among these items is a 151 piece section of correspondence to and from Conde Antonio de Perez Galvez from 1808, and a section of 86 documents relating to Puerto Rico from the 1850s. There are also State documents relating to San Luis Potosi and other Mexican States, and a 1831 hymn book from Santa Teresa de Jesus, Mexico. Due to the age and fragile nature of these documents, they are placed in protective sleeves and cannot be removed. Please use caution in handling them.

bioghist.head: Biography/Profile
bioghist.p: The Early Texas Documents series contains general correspondence, legal documents such as land grants and titles, wills, marriage licenses, court documents and legal representation documents. It also contains financial documents such as treasury warrants, bonds, inventories and numerous pieces of currency from the Republic of Texas as well as the Civil War period. Rounding out this series are documents in German, French and Latin, flyers, sheet music, invitations, tickets, circulars, and publications.

bioghist.head: Biography/Profile
bioghist.p: The correspondence subseries consists of general correspondence with no set theme or groupings. Of particular note is one letter to General S.F. Austin, Branch F. Archer and William H. Wharton from October 16, 1835, relating that "Bexar has fallen!"

bioghist.head: Biography/Profile
bioghist.p: The legal subseries is the largest of the Early Texas Documents and consists of materials covering land grants, land titles, wills, marriages, court documents, and documents pertaining to legal representation. In some cases, there are more than one document for a particular person, but most are stand alone items. Rare signatures such as Moses Austin, Stephen F. Austin, and Sam Houston can be found in this subseries.

bioghist.head: Biography/Profile
bioghist.p: The third subseries, financial, is made up of financial documents in the form of treasury warrants, inventories, receipts, bonds, Republic of Texas and Civil War currency, and checks. As with the other subseries in this section, most of the documents are stand alone items and have no connection to others in the subseries. The Republic of Texas and Civil War currency are interesting for the range and variety of notes.

bioghist.p: Other is the fourth subseries and contains materials in languages other than English and Spanish, such as German, French, and Latin. It also holds early flyers, sheet music, invitations, tickets, circulars, publications, and a section of letters and documents from the Arthur Stiles family. The Stiles family materials are three document boxes of correspondence and business records from Arthur's surveying business.

bioghist.p: The Early United States Documents series contains early documents relating to the United States apart from Texas. Confederate State currency, United States currency, bank notes and script from non-Texas states, treasury warrants, United States treaties with individual Indian tribes, and correspondence call be found in this section of the papers.
